Hereby, data generated in the âTransversal Analysis of MEA dataâ document is analysed.

First, we load the database MEA_segments that we will use to perform the study. This is the list of the 30 second periods with more movement in the MEA videos. The criterion used is for the movement in the period to be higher than the median, and that this has to hold for both subjects (patient and therapist).

The database has 857 observations of 19 variables.

Below, we show the entries of a few observations in the database.

Take a look into the lags where the maximum positive and negative cross correlations are found.

Split the database in two: database MEA_segments_pos and MEA_segments_neg according with the type of correlation found (positive or negative). Remove the entries with lags small (less than a quarter of a second). Also, keep only the entries with moderate and high cross correlations (absolute values above 0.35).

With such criteria, there are 347 with positive correlation and 379 with negative correlation. Visualize the lags

And the lags with the value of the correlation

An overview of the variables of interest, classified into diagnosed subjects vs control subjects.
